A fire struck Mexico City’s downtown subway headquarters early on Saturday, officials said. Smoke billowed out of the multi-story building roof, causing at least one death and light injuries. Six lines of the capital’s sprawling subway lines were knocked offline due to the fire, which was believed to be caused by an electricity failure. ABUJA DOCTOR REVEALS HOW MOST NIGERIA MEN ARE NOW OVERCOMING TERRIBLE BEDROOM PERFORMANCE DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY. DON'T BE A VICTIM! Mayor Claudia Sheinbaum told reporters near the building that the early morning fire was “practically extinguished as teams of firefighters and water tanks remained at the scene’’. Sheinbaum said one police officer, who had likely slipped and fallen into the flames, was confirmed dead. Indonesian Plane Crashes After Take-Off With 62 Aboard Donald Trump To Miss Inauguration She said 30 people had been transported to local hospitals due mostly to smoke inhalation. Officials said the fire began around 5.00 a.m. local time and investigators from the city government as well as Mexico’s national electricity company, CFE, were evaluating damages and the exact cause of the accident. While daily newspaper, El Universal, reported earlier on Saturday that as many as 10 people remained trapped inside the building, Sheinbaum suggested that everyone inside had already been rescued.